## Answers to All Six Design Questions

---

### 1. CSS Application Strategy: Option B (data-theme attribute) is correct

**Use Option B: set `data-theme` on `<html>` and define CSS rules per theme in `index.css`.**

The reasoning from the codebase confirms this:

**FOUC prevention is the deciding factor.** The existing `useTheme.ts` calls `applyTheme(getStored())` at module load time — before React renders anything. That call runs as a side effect when the JS module is first evaluated. With Option B, you change one attribute on `<html>` synchronously and the CSS engine resolves all vars instantly. With Option A (`setProperty()` per-var), you would need to call `setProperty()` for every custom property (~22 vars) on every page load, and you risk a visible flash if that JS hasn't parsed yet — but more critically, you lose the ability to express the theme in CSS at all, breaking SSR, print stylesheets, and any tooling that reads computed styles.

**Maintainability strongly favors Option B.** The existing pattern in `index.css` already uses `@variant dark { ... }` blocks inside `:root` to express theme overrides declaratively. Option B follows the same philosophy: all theme definitions live in one CSS file, each theme is self-contained, and adding a fourth theme later requires only a new CSS block with no JS changes. Option A scatters color definitions across JS, breaking the separation of concerns that the existing codebase follows.

**No-transitions compatibility.** The existing `.no-transitions` suppression class in `index.css` works at the CSS level. Both options are equally compatible with it — the `no-transitions` class is toggled in `applyTheme()` before the attribute/class change, then removed in the next rAF, which covers the CSS cascade update regardless of which option you choose.

**The one nuance:** keep the attribute write synchronous (no async, no `requestAnimationFrame`) in the module-load `applyTheme()` call, just as the current `.dark` class toggle is synchronous. That eliminates FOUC entirely.

---

### 2. Dark class + data-theme coexistence

The `.dark` class and `data-theme` attribute serve different purposes and must coexist:

- `data-theme="t3-dark"` or `data-theme="t3-midnight"` drives your custom CSS property values.
- `.dark` on `<html>` drives Tailwind's `dark:` utility prefix (via `@custom-variant dark (&:is(.dark, .dark *))`).

The updated `applyTheme()` function must do both writes atomically:

```
function applyTheme(theme: Theme, suppressTransitions = false) {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight; // force reflow
  }

  const resolved = resolveTheme(theme); // returns "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight"
  const isDark = resolved === "t3-dark" || resolved === "t3-midnight";

  document.documentElement.setAttribute("data-theme", resolved);
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}
```

The mapping for `system` is: if `prefers-color-scheme: dark` → resolve to `"t3-dark"`, else `"t3-light"`. Users who had dark system preference get the default dark theme; light preference gets the default light theme. This can be made more sophisticated later (e.g., store a preferred dark theme and a preferred light theme separately), but the simple version is sufficient for the initial migration.

**Critical note on the `color-scheme` property:** The current CSS uses `color-scheme: light` on `:root` and `color-scheme: dark` inside the `@variant dark` block. With the new system, move `color-scheme` into each per-theme block in CSS:

```css
html[data-theme="t3-light"] { color-scheme: light; ... }
html[data-theme="t3-dark"]  { color-scheme: dark;  ... }
html[data-theme="t3-midnight"] { color-scheme: dark; ... }
```

This ensures browser chrome (scrollbars, form controls, etc.) matches each theme correctly without relying on the `.dark` class to set it.

---

### 3. CSS selector specificity

**Use `html[data-theme="t3-dark"] { ... }` directly. Do not use `html[data-theme="t3-dark"] :root { ... }`.**

The reason is precise: `:root` is a pseudo-class selector that matches `<html>`. So `html[data-theme="t3-dark"] :root` would mean "a `:root` element that is a descendant of `html[data-theme="t3-dark"]`" — which matches nothing, because `<html>` cannot be its own descendant.

`html[data-theme="t3-dark"]` directly targets the `<html>` element (which is also `:root`), so CSS custom properties set there are inherited by all descendants, exactly as the existing `:root { ... }` declarations work.

The specificity of `html[data-theme="t3-dark"]` is `(0,1,1)` — one attribute selector + one type selector — which is higher than the bare `:root` specificity of `(0,1,0)`. This means the themed overrides will correctly win over the base `:root` defaults without needing `!important`.

The existing `@variant dark { ... }` block inside `:root` expands to `.dark :root { ... }` (or equivalent), giving it `(0,1,1)` specificity. The new `html[data-theme]` selectors match that weight exactly, so there is no conflict when both coexist during the transition period. Once you remove the `@variant dark` block from inside `:root`, you have a clean separation.

---

### 4. t3-midnight color palette

t3-midnight is a deep blue-navy theme — not black-neutral like t3-dark. The background should feel like the deep ocean or a star-filled sky, with blue-tinted surfaces and a slightly warmer purple primary. Here are concrete values:

```css
html[data-theme="t3-midnight"] {
  color-scheme: dark;

  /* Backgrounds: deep navy, not neutral black */
  --background: #0a0f1e;           /* Very deep navy */
  --foreground: #e2e8f4;           /* Cool off-white, blue-tinted */

  /* Cards / popovers: slightly lighter navy surface */
  --card: #0f1629;
  --card-foreground: #e2e8f4;
  --popover: #0f1629;
  --popover-foreground: #e2e8f4;

  /* Primary: brighter, more electric purple-blue (distinct from t3-dark's oklch(0.588 0.217 264)) */
  --primary: oklch(0.65 0.22 258);      /* ~#7c6fff — slightly more blue-shifted, higher lightness */
  --primary-foreground: #ffffff;

  /* Secondary / muted / accent: white-on-navy at low alpha, with a blue tint */
  --secondary: color-mix(in srgb, #4a6fa5 8%, transparent);
  --secondary-foreground: #e2e8f4;
  --muted: color-mix(in srgb, #4a6fa5 8%, transparent);
  --muted-foreground: #7a94c1;          /* Desaturated blue-grey for subdued text */
  --accent: color-mix(in srgb, #4a6fa5 10%, transparent);
  --accent-foreground: #e2e8f4;

  /* Destructive */
  --destructive: #f87171;               /* Same as t3-dark red-400 equivalent, good on dark bg */
  --destructive-foreground: #fca5a5;    /* red-300 */

  /* Borders and inputs: navy-tinted white at low alpha */
  --border: color-mix(in srgb, #4a90e2 10%, transparent);   /* blue-tinted border */
  --input: color-mix(in srgb, #4a90e2 13%, transparent);
  --ring: oklch(0.65 0.22 258);         /* matches primary */

  /* Semantic colors: same hues as t3-dark, these are fine on dark backgrounds */
  --info: #60a5fa;                      /* blue-400 */
  --info-foreground: #93c5fd;           /* blue-300 */
  --success: #34d399;                   /* emerald-400 */
  --success-foreground: #6ee7b7;        /* emerald-300 */
  --warning: #fbbf24;                   /* amber-400 */
  --warning-foreground: #fcd34d;        /* amber-300 */
}
```

**Design rationale:** The background at `#0a0f1e` reads as deep midnight navy, not charcoal. Cards at `#0f1629` create subtle depth without looking like a different application. The `--muted-foreground` of `#7a94c1` is recognisably blue-grey, making it feel distinct from t3-dark's neutral-grey muted text. The borders use `#4a90e2` at 10% alpha which gives a faint blue glow to dividers — a characteristic midnight/IDE aesthetic. The primary is shifted 6 hue degrees bluer than t3-dark's `264` and bumped to lightness `0.65` so it pops more on the darker navy background.

---

